Good question — this confuses most people when they start Ansible AWS dynamic inventory.

Let’s break it simply.

🧠 Why Python3 is required?

Ansible itself is written in Python.

When you use AWS dynamic inventory like:

plugin: amazon.aws.aws_ec2

👉 Ansible internally runs a Python plugin to:

connect to AWS
fetch EC2 instances
apply filters (tags, regions, etc.)

So Python3 is required because:

Ansible executes inventory plugins using Python runtime
Without Python → plugin cannot run
☁️ Why boto3 is required?

👉 boto3 is the AWS SDK for Python

It allows Python (and Ansible) to talk to AWS APIs.

So when Ansible runs dynamic inventory, it does:

Ansible plugin → Python → boto3 → AWS API → EC2 data
🔥 Simple flow
Ansible
   ↓
aws_ec2 plugin (Python code)
   ↓
boto3 library
   ↓
AWS API (EC2, tags, regions)
   ↓
Returns list of instances
🧠 Real-world analogy

Think like this:

Component	Role
Ansible	Manager
Python	Language used by manager
boto3	AWS translator
AWS	Data source (EC2 instances)

👉 Without boto3 → Python cannot talk to AWS
👉 Without Python → Ansible plugin cannot run

📦 What happens if boto3 is missing?

You’ll see errors like:

botocore.exceptions.NoModuleError: No module named boto3

or

ImportError: boto3 not found

👉 Meaning: “I don’t know how to connect to AWS”

⚙️ Why Ansible doesn’t do AWS calls directly?

Because:

AWS APIs are complex
Authentication, signing requests is hard
boto3 already solves this

So Ansible reuses boto3 instead of reinventing AWS integration

🧪 Installation

Usually required:

pip install boto3 botocore

or

pip3 install boto3
🎯 Final simple answer

👉 Python3 is required because Ansible AWS plugins run in Python
👉 boto3 is required because it is the library that actually talks to AWS APIs

